## 12.2 Material Justification
Explain why you selected your main materials and components.

Examples:
- Why acrylic instead of cardboard?
- Why MDF instead of 3D print?
- Why servo instead of DC motor?
- Why bearing instead of a plain shaft hole?

**Response:**  
`[The ESP32 was chosen as the core microcontroller because it has built-in capacitive touch pins, which directly solved our gesture detection problem without 
 requiring any additional sensor modules or analog calibration. Its native USB serial support also made communicating with the Python game on the laptop 
 straightforward. We initially chose flex sensors because they are the conventional choice for finger bend detection in glove projects. However, after persistent 
 calibration difficulties and heat damage caused by soldering, we pivoted to the ESP32's built-in capacitive touch pins. This was a simpler and more reliable 
 solution — touch pins give a clean binary signal requiring no threshold tuning or voltage dividers. A thin glove was chosen over a rigid housing because the project
 needs to be wearable and allow full natural hand movement. A rigid structure would restrict the fingers and make gestures uncomfortable to perform. 
 The thin material also makes it easy to attach conductive wires and route cables neatly along the back of the hand. Jumper wires and a breadboard were used 
 throughout instead of a custom PCB because they allow rapid changes during prototyping. Every time a sensor was swapped, or a pin changed, 
 the breadboard made reconfiguration a matter of seconds rather than requiring new solder joints.]`

