If your cost is too high, what can be simplified, removed, substituted, or shared?

**Response:**  
`[The overall cost of this project was very low because most of the core electronics were available in the school kit. The ESP32, breadboard, resistors and jumper 
 wires were all provided, which meant the only out-of-pocket costs were the glove, conductive wire and replacement sensors. The most expensive individual component 
 was the flex sensor at 199rs per unit, and we purchased three of them. In hindsight, this was unnecessary since we ultimately switched to capacitive touch sensors , 
 which are built directly into the ESP32 and cost nothing extra. If we were starting the project again, we would skip the flex sensors entirely and go straight to 
 touch sensors, saving approximately 597rs. The project could be made even cheaper by using any spare fabric glove instead of buying one, and by using stripped 
 copper wire from old electronics instead of buying fresh conductive wire. ]`

