# 18. Final Outcome

## 18.1 Final Description
Describe the final version of your project.

**Response:**  
`[NeonKnuckle is a gesture-controlled Rock Paper Scissors fight game built using an ESP32 microcontroller, capacitive touch sensors embedded in a glove, 
 and a fullscreen Python Pygame application running on a laptop. The player wears the glove and makes hand gestures to play against the CPU. 
 Touch wires on the index, middle and ring fingers detect gestures which are sent over USB serial to the game. 
 The game features a cinematic pixel art UI with health bars, a countdown timer, particle explosions, retro sound effects and a full match system where the first 
 player to lose 5 rounds loses the match.]`

## 18.2 What Works Well
- `[Capacitive touch sensors detect gestures instantly and reliably with no calibration needed]`
- `[The game UI is fully functional with smooth animations, sounds, health bars and match logic]`
- `[The serial communication between ESP32 and the game is stable and responsive]`

## 18.3 What Still Needs Improvement
- `[The glove wiring is still temporary with jumper wires and tape, a cleaner permanent solution with soldered connections and proper strain relief would make it more durable]`
- `[The ESP32 and breadboard are currently kept on the desk rather than mounted on the glove, a fully wireless version using BLE and a powerbank would make it truly wearable]`
- `[The touch sensors occasionally trigger from static or accidental contact, adding a debounce delay or requiring the gesture to be held for a minimum duration would improve accuracy]`

## 18.4 What Changed From the Original Plan
How did the project change from the initial idea?

**Response:**  
`[The original plan used flex sensors in a voltage divider circuit to detect finger bending. This was abandoned after persistent calibration issues and heat damage 
 from soldering made the sensors unreliable. The project pivoted to capacitive touch sensors using the ESP32's built-in touch pins, which proved far simpler and 
 more reliable. The wireless Bluetooth approach was also planned but not implemented in the final version due to time constraints.
 The project currently uses USB serial communication instead.]`

