# 19. Reflection

## 19.1 Team Reflection
What did your team do well?  
What slowed you down?  
How well did you manage time, tasks, and responsibilities?

**Response:**  
`[Our team worked well together on splitting the hardware and software sides of the project. Yagya focused heavily on the game code and ESP32 firmware while
 Ananya assisted with the physical glove assembly and sensor testing. We communicated well when things broke and made decisions quickly.
 The pivot from flex sensors to touch sensors happened in one session once we agreed the flex approach was not going to work reliably in time. What slowed us down 
most was the flex sensor troubleshooting. We spent a significant amount of time trying to calibrate thresholds, rewiring circuits and replacing damaged sensors 
 before realising the fundamental problem was the soldering damaging the sensors. In hindsight, we should have tested the sensors more thoroughly before committing 
to soldering. Time management was reasonable overall. The software was completed well ahead of the hardware, which gave us flexibility to iterate on the game 
while the hardware was being sorted. The final integration came together quickly once we switched to touch sensors.]`

## 19.2 Technical Reflection
What did you learn about:
- electronics,
- coding,
- mechanisms,
- fabrication,
- integration?

**Response:**  
`[On the electronics side, we learned how voltage dividers work and how ADC pins on the ESP32 read analogue signals. We also learned the hard way that flex sensors 
 are heat sensitive and that soldering directly to thin sensor pins requires speed and precision. Switching to capacitive touch taught us that sometimes a simpler 
 solution is the better solution. The ESP32's built-in touch pins eliminated an entire layer of complexity that was causing us problems. On the coding side, we learned
 how serial communication works between a microcontroller and a Python application, how to generate sound programmatically using numpy without any audio files, 
 and how to build a full-screen game loop in Pygame with multiple states, animations and particle effects. We also learned how MicroPython differs from standard 
 Python and how to save and run code on embedded hardware using Thonny.On the integration side, we learned how important it is to test each component in isolation 
 before combining them. Every time we tried to jump ahead and combine untested parts, we ran into problems that were hard to debug.]`

## 19.3 Design Reflection
What did you learn about:
- designing for play,
- delight,
- clarity,
- physical interaction,
- player understanding,
- iteration?

**Response:**  
`[Designing for play taught us that the interaction needs to feel natural and immediate. The original flex sensor approach had a delay and inconsistency that broke
 the flow of the game. Players would make a gesture, and nothing would happen, which felt broken. The touch sensor approach fixed this instantly and made the game feel
 responsive and satisfying. We learned that clarity in feedback is essential. Adding the Rock... Paper... Scissors... Shoot! 
 countdown made the game immediately understandable to anyone watching without any explanation needed. The health bars, particle explosions and sound effects all 
 reinforced what was happening on screen and made wins and losses feel impactful. Physical interaction taught us that wearable tech needs to be comfortable and 
 unobtrusive. The glove felt natural to wear, and the touch wires did not interfere with hand movement. We iterated on the sensor placement multiple times to find 
 positions that detected gestures reliably without false triggers. Player understanding improved significantly through playtesting. 
 We realised early on that players needed visual feedback during the timer showing their locked-in gesture, otherwise they were unsure if their input had registered.]`

## 19.4 If You Had One More Week
What would you improve next?

**Response:**  
`[With one more week, we would implement the wireless Bluetooth version using the ESP32's BLE capabilities and a small powerbank mounted on the wrist. 
 This would make the glove fully untethered and wearable anywhere without needing a USB cable running to the laptop.
 We would also clean up the glove wiring by replacing the jumper wires and tape with properly soldered connections, heat shrink tubing and a neat cable channel along
 the back of the glove. Finally, we would add the OLED screen on the glove showing the player's remaining lives in real time so they would not need to look at the 
 laptop screen during play.]`

